name="venue">Higher Structures</fr:meta><fr:meta
name="bibtex"><![CDATA[@article{christensen-opie-rijke-scoccola-2020,
  author = {Christensen, J. Daniel and Opie, Morgan and Rijke, Egbert and Scoccola, Luis},
  publisher = {Institute of Mathematics CAS},
  year = {2020},
  month = feb,
  doi = {10.21136/HS.2020.01},
  issue = {1},
  journal = {Higher Structures},
  pages = {1--32},
  title = {Localization in Homotopy Type Theory},
  volume = {4},
}]]></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We study localization at a prime in homotopy type theory, using self maps of the circle. Our main result is that for a pointed, simply connected type <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, the natural map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X \rightarrow  X_{(p)}]]></fr:tex> induces algebraic localizations on all homotopy groups. In order to prove this, we further develop the theory of reflective subuniverses. In particular, we show that for any reflective subuniverse <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>, the subuniverse of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>-separated types is again a reflective subuniverse, which we call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L']]></fr:tex>. Furthermore, we prove results establishing that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L']]></fr:tex> is almost left exact. We next focus on localization with respect to a map, giving results on preservation of coproducts and connectivity. We also study how such localizations interact with other reflective subuniverses and orthogonal factorization systems. As key steps towards proving the main theorem, we show that localization at a prime commutes with taking loop spaces for a pointed, simply connected type, and explicitly describe the localization of an Eilenberg-Mac Lane space <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K(G,n)]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> abelian. We also include a partial converse to the main theorem.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
